<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFrameworks>net8.0;net10.0</TargetFrameworks>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <PackageId>FluxFlow.Components.State</PackageId>
    <AssemblyName>FluxFlow.Components.State</AssemblyName>
    <RootNamespace>FluxFlow.Components.State</RootNamespace>
    <Version>2.0.0</Version>
    <Authors>FluxFlow contributors</Authors>
    <Description>A standalone keyed state-reducer node for FluxFlow: a reducer input in, an updated state snapshot broadcast out, per-key state kept in the node. No engine required.</Description>
    <PackageTags>workflow;dataflow;components;state;reducer</PackageTags>
    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>
    <PackageReleaseNotes>Rebuilt as a single standalone state.reducer node over the FluxFlow.Nodes kit: a StateReducerInput in, a StateReducerResult broadcast out, reducer/key failures on the error port — all carrying the message correlation id, with per-operation notes and key-limit warnings on the events port. The reducer (and optional key) expression is compiled once at construction. The engine factory, module, registration extensions, design-metadata provider, definition-options reader, component type/port constants, and the expression-engine registry wrapper are removed; the node takes its options, an IFlowExpressionEngine, and a TimeProvider directly and depends only on FluxFlow.Nodes and FluxFlow.Mapping (runs without the engine).</PackageReleaseNotes>
    <RepositoryType>git</RepositoryType>
    <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>
    <IncludeSymbols>true</IncludeSymbols>
    <SymbolPackageFormat>snupkg</SymbolPackageFormat>
  </PropertyGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <ProjectReference Include="..\FluxFlow.Mapping\FluxFlow.Mapping.csproj" />
    <ProjectReference Include="..\FluxFlow.Nodes\FluxFlow.Nodes.csproj" />
  </ItemGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <None Include="README.md" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
